T1  - Can learning affect exchange-rate behavior?: The case of the dollar in the early 1980's
AU  - Lewis, Karen K.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
SP  - 79
EP  - 100
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(89)90063-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393289900639
AB  - This paper demonstrates that a change in parameters of the money market that is not immediately understood will affect the behavior of exchange-rate forecast errors while the market is learning. The analysis is applied to the behavior of U.S. dollar-German mark forecast errors during the early 1980's when the market appeared to systematically underpredict the strength of the dollar. Consistent with this observation, empirical estimates of implied forecast errors based upon Bayesian learning suggest that forecast errors would have been on-average negative during the period as the market came to realize the increase in U.S. money demand.
