T1  - A theory of a generally acceptable medium of exchange and barter
AU  - Oh, Seonghwan
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
SP  - 101
EP  - 119
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(89)90064-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393289900640
AB  - This paper develops a model that accounts both for the existence of money, defined as a generally acceptable medium of exchange, and for the survival of some barter exchange in economies in which money exists. In contrast to Jones' (1976) seminal article in which individuals are restricted to fix trading strategies before entering the market, the present model assumes that individuals have conditional trading strategies that allow them to effect exchange according to the types of trades they encounter in the market. The analysis shows how decentralized market forces generate money and lead to a unique level of monetization.
